{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511392"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:42:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:42:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11748"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11748"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.43,0.14,0.1,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114825"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4361"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11748"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96829"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"625"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6504"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19119"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48433"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114825"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a four month history of intermittent right upper quadrant pain. Each episode of pain would last about one hour, be constant in nature and then resolve spontaneously. He does not have any other health issues, does not drink alcohol and smokes about 10 cigarettes a day. He migrated from Afghanistan about two years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe physical examination is unremarkable and a CT is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In regards to the demonstrated abnormal liver lesions, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance alone","Hydatid serology","Fine needle aspiration","Percutaneous drainage","Albendazole"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows several well defined, hypodense and homogenous lesions in the liver. These are simple liver cysts and will have been an incidental finding. It is very unlikely that these would explain this patient\u0027s symptoms, which, if anything, could have been episodes of biliary colic. Most liver cysts never produce any symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is estimated that some 5% of the population will have such cystic lesions in their liver and perhaps some 10-15% of these individuals will have symptoms that can be directly attributable to the cysts. The differential diagnoses to consider with these cystic lesions would include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epolycystic liver disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eparasitic cysts (echinococcus)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ecystic tumours\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eabscesses\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn polycystic liver disease, the cystic lesions would predominate over the normal liver parenchyma. Whilst this patient does come from a part of the world where hydatid disease is found, the lesions in her liver do not resemble Echinococcal cysts. These are usually unifocal and have a clear rim of calcification. Cystic tumours would have a heterogenous appearance, as would abscesses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the cysts are almost certainly incidental findings, no further action needs to be taken and a \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance\u003C/strong\u003E approach is all that is needed. The patient is likely presenting with recurrent biliary colic which should be treated in its own right with an outpatient elective laparoscopic however this is unrelated to the incidentally identified liver lesions. A \u003Cstrong\u003Efine needle aspiration biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E would only be done if it was thought that the lesion might be malignant - such as a metastatic deposit. If the possibility of an hepatocellular carcinoma was raised, tissue biopsy would be avoided (risk of seeding) if liver transplantation was to be considered. \u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for potentially infective lesions. \u003Cstrong\u003EAlbendazole\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for the treatment of hydatid disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most liver cysts are incidental findings that do not need any further evaluation."],"references":["Mavilia MG, Pakala T, Molina M et al.Differentiating Cystic Liver Lesions: A Review of Imaging Modalities, Diagnosis and Management. J Clin Transl Hepatol 2018 28; 6:208-16."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96829"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11748"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19983"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19983"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e2f5ff73-ba01-4ffa-accf-5969cff10b22.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e2f5ff73-ba01-4ffa-accf-5969cff10b22.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":536,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96829"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17